******************************* БРАВО IBM ********************************
***** IBM OS/2 2.1 Beta Version заслужила аплодисменты пользователей *****

    The beta-test version of IBM's OS/2 Version  2.1  has  been  available
 since Dec. 19 now, and users generally seem happy with  its  performance.
 However, some say they hope IBM makes sure this  version  goes  out  rock
 solid in  order  to  silence  OS/2  critics.  ``Somehow  IBM  has  gotten
 themselves into this position of people expecting a lot  more  from  them
 than they ever did from Microsoft,'' said Larry Waibel,  systems software
 technical specialist at the Cubic Automated Revenue Collection  Group  in
 San Diego. He said he hopes IBM makes this version of  OS/2  bulletproof,
 though he conceded it is  not  quite  there  yet.  ``I've  had  a  couple
 hang-ups in the two months I've been using it, which is  certainly better
 than anybody got in Windows,'' Waibel said.

    ``We're all on your side here -- we want OS/2 to succeed,''  said  one
 developer on CompuServe. ``Another rush job is exactly  what  it  doesn't
 need.'' Currently, beta-test users  are  still  reporting  problems  with
 installation, applications that ran under  OS/2  2.0  ``breaking''  under
 OS/2 2.1 and ``memory leaks'' that force  users  to  reboot  the  machine
 every so often.  However,  reports  of  dramatic  improvements  are  also
 cropping up. Waibel said the best features  of  the  OS/2  2.1  beta-test
 version are improved graphics handling and support for higher resolutions
 and Windows 3.1.

************* КОММЕРЧЕСКИЙ ВЫПУСК OS/2 2.1 ОЖИДАЕТСЯ В МАЕ ***************

 Although beta testers of IBM's OS/2 2.1 generally favor the product,
 sources last week said they don't expect the final version to be
 available until May. IBM has pushed its delivery goal of the first
 quarter back another six to eight weeks to ensure fixes to a variety of
 minor but persistent bugs. Although it is doubtful the delay will
 seriously damage the product's chances against Microsoft Corp.'s Windows
 3.1, it does increase the company's pressures to release a version that
 is rock solid. "We have looked at OS/2, but my worry is they [IBM] don't
 have a lot of time left," said Brian Moura, assistant city manager for
 the city of San Carlos, Calif. "They may need two or three more revs to
 get it all right, but they may not have that time," he said.

 With a May delivery, IBM may run up against Microsoft's mammoth
 marketing of Windows NT, which is set to begin in May at Windows World,
 sources said. However, the final version of Windows NT is not expected
 until June. "IBM needs to make something happen with 2.1, or it's facing
 the possibility of being a niche product for a very long time," said one
 developer who requested his name be withheld. The bulk of the OS/2 2.1
 problems that are being addressed revolve around making it work better
 with Windows applications and improving the operating system's
 installation with lesser known or generic clones. One of the most
 important additions to Version 2.1 is complete support of Microsoft's
 Windows 3.1. Although there is not a rich array of applications that
 take full advantage of Windows 3.1, it is a strong requirement for some
 corporate buyers. Some developers said the delay is holding up their
 release of maintenance versions for existing OS/2 applications.

 "A slip in their schedule causes us grief because we are planning a
 maintenance release to fix things in our products," said another
 experienced OS/2 developer. "Now we might have to do another release to
 fix changes in their [OS/2 2.1] code. Still, as it stands now, it is
 much more complete than 2.0 was on the day it shipped," he added. An IBM
 representative declined to comment on the story.
