******************  МИКРОСОФТ ОБРЕЗАЕТ УШИ У MS-DOS 6.0 ****************

 Microsoft Corp. has pulled network and mail functions from DOS 6.0 and
 has also removed some data compression features in an apparent response
 to a patent-infringement suit. The Microsoft Mail client and Workgroup
 Connection, which provides a link to Windows for Workgroups (WFW), have
 been removed from DOS 6.0, a Microsoft official said last week.
 Corporate users who already have other networks installed requested that
 Microsoft remove the network components so users would not "start
 messing around with a different network," said Brad Chase, Microsoft's
 general manager of MS-DOS. Both networking components had been promised
 for DOS 6.0 when it ships next month or in early April. The network
 software will be removed from the retail upgrade product, although users
 can still buy the functionality separately, Chase said. In addition, PC
 vendors who bundle DOS 6.0 may include the network portions. Meanwhile,
 an off-line feature of DOS 6.0's DoubleSpace data compression utility,
 called MaxCompress, has also been removed from the beta. The feature may
 still be included when DOS 6.0 ships, he said.

 Stac Electronics sued Microsoft last month over the DoubleSpace utility,
 alleging it infringes patents Stac holds on its data compression
 products. A source close to both companies said pulling the MaxCompress
 feature would not likely deter Stac from continuing its suit. The case
 is not expected to go to trial until late this year. Many users have
 said built-in data compression is a very important feature for DOS 6.0's
 success. As MaxCompress is an off-line feature meant to be run
 overnight, removing it will not impact DoubleSpace's effectiveness,
 Chase said. Some analysts suggested Microsoft's latest moves may be an
 effort to rethink its overall network marketing strategy. "InfoWorld"
 reported last week that WFW sales were dragging. "Customers seem to be
 willing to buy as many flavors of Windows as Microsoft wants to sell but
 are balking at buying more than one flavor of network," said Jeffrey
 Tarter, publisher of "SoftLetter." In a notice Microsoft sent out last
 week about its DOS 6.0 plans, it referred to the product as Release
 Candidate 4, a name that indicates the product will ship soon, observers
 said.
