****************** НОВАЯ СИСТЕМА ПЕЧАТИ НА ЛАЗЕРЕ ДЛЯ WINDOWS *************

    Microsoft has announced the immediate availability  of  the  Microsoft
 Windows Printing System. The software provides an easier and  faster  way
 for users of Windows 3.1 to print from PCs  to  Hewlett-Packard  LaserJet
 Series II and III printers.
    The Windows Printing System provides  speed,  easy  to  use  graphical
 printer controls, bi- directional communication between  printer  and  PC
 and  faithful  what-you-see-is-what-  you-get  (WYSIWYG)   support   with
 TrueType fonts.
    Since the Windows Printing System brings Windows from the  PC  to  the
 printer, the system  no  longer  requires  time-  consuming  translations
 between the PC and page description languages that reside on the printer.
 Microsoft says this translates into significantly faster  printing that's
 up to five times  faster  than  PCL  and  up  to  10  times  faster  than
 PostScript.
    At the same time, notes Microsoft, the Windows Printing  System  makes
 it easier for users to both understand and access the  printing  process.
 Taking advantage of the graphical user interface capabilities of Windows,
 the Windows Printing System provides users with an on-  screen  graphical
 control panel. The panel includes animated images of  whichever supported
 printer is connected to the PC, as well as icon-based  printer  and  page
 configuration  options,  real-time  visual  error  and   printer   status
 reporting, print time estimation and animated  status  of  each  printing
 job.
    The Windows Printing System has three components: software for the PC,
 including 79 TrueType fonts; software for the printer;  and  a  cartridge
 that plugs into the printer's standard  cartridge  slot.  Together,  they
 link the printer to the PC to manage and enhance the printing  process in
 real time.
    "There are 6.5 million installed  Hewlett-Packard  LaserJet  printers,
 and there is a tremendous amount of overlap between  those  printers  and
 users of Windows,"  says  Steve  Shaiman,  general  manager  of  systems,
 peripherals and accessories group at  Microsoft.  "That  creates  a  very
 large target market for the Windows Printing System,  and  we  think  the
 clear performance and ease-  of-use  benefits  of  the  Windows  Printing
 System make it a great printing solution under Windows."
    The Windows Printing System is currently available in  Australia,  the
 U.K. and the U.S. through resellers for a suggested list  price  of  $199
 (U.S. only).
