*** ПЕРВЫЕ ПРОЦЕССОРЫ  OverDrive Pentium БУДУТ ОТГРУЖЕНЫ ТОЛЬКО В 1994 ***

 Users expecting to get the power of the Pentium this year with their
 current 486 systems that have a Pentium upgrade socket will be
 disappointed. Intel Corp. isn't expected to ship the OverDrive Pentium
 processor, code-named the P24T, until 1994. According to some PC makers,
 who included a Pentium upgrade socket with their latest 486 systems,
 Intel was supposed to roll out the P24T within a few weeks of the
 introduction of the full- scale Pentium this spring. But they said last
 week that Intel is telling them not to expect the chip until at least
 next year. Although systems have been sold since the second half of 1992
 as "Pentium ready," manufacturers say the frustration of the delay will
 be tempered by Intel's plans to introduce a 486DX3/99 processor later
 this year that will help fill the gap. An Intel representative denied
 that there was any delay concerning the OverDrive processor, noting that
 OverDrive processors traditionally are announced after the main
 processor is announced.

 The first OverDrive processors, however, were introduced within 60 days
 of their 486DX2/50 and 486DX2/66 OEM counterparts. Intel is expected to
 formally introduce the Pentium on March 22, but in an unusual twist,
 Intel is requiring that PC makers keep their Pentium-based machines
 under wraps until May. "If I was Intel and I looked at how many 486
 processors I was able to sell and the limited market for the Pentium
 initially, I would probably focus on the 486 this year as well," said
 Dean McCarron, a senior analyst for the market research firm InStat, in
 Tempe, Ariz. "The situation would have been different if [Advanced Micro
 Devices Inc.] had been able to ship its 486 clone early this year." At
 the Software Developers Conference in San Jose, Calif., this week, Intel
 and a host of other companies, including IBM and Microsoft Corp., will
 announce a number of tools designed to help develop 32-bit applications.
 They will also announce a new generation of compilers that will let
 software developers take advantage of the Pentium's superscalar
 capabilities.
