********  U.S. Trade Commission РЕШИЛА ПРЕКРАТИТЬ РАССЛЕДОВАНИЕ **********
*** О НАРУШЕНИИ ФИРМАЙ МИКРОСОФТ АНТИМОНОПОЛЬНОГО ЗАКОНОДАТЕЛЬСТВА *******

 The computer industry's ears perked up in anticipation this week after
 the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) said it would soon make an
 announcement concerning a ``nonpublic investigation'' generally regarded
 as the Microsoft Corp. antitrust case. But instead of clearing the
 smoke, the FTC managed to fog the issue even more, after apparently
 deciding not to decide the case after two years of investigation. In a
 terse statement, the FTC indicated it would meet shortly to discuss the
 situation further.

 Reports had circulated that the FTC's lawyers recommended an injunction
 against Microsoft, possibly concerning its MS-DOS licensing practices.
 The FTC could have voted to accept that recommendation, deny it or
 extend the investigation. Previous speculation that the FTC might seek
 to split Microsoft into applications and operating systems segments have
 generally been disregarded. What happens now is anyone's guess.
 According to George Cumming Jr., a trial lawyer at Brobeck, Phleger &
 Harrison in San Francisco, the lack of a decision simply indicates that
 the FTC feels it needs more time. That time could be spent gathering
 more information, discussing the lawyer's recommendations more
 thoroughly, or possibly, working out a settlement with Microsoft
 attorneys.

 ``It's kind of difficult to read into the thing,'' Cumming said. For its
 part, Microsoft said it is continuing to cooperate with the FTC but that
 otherwise business is going on as usual. Novell, Inc., which is widely
 rumored to be preparing a class-action antitrust suit against Microsoft,
 said it will have no comment on the FTC investigation until a decision
 is rendered. Wall Street watchers said it seemed strange that the FTC
 would be unable to render a decision after more than two years. One
 possibility is that the FTC may be deadlocked. One of the five members
 of the investigating committee reportedly removed himself for
 conflict-of-interest reasons shortly before the decision was to be made
 public. That created a situation where a tie was possible. At least
 three of the five members would have to vote either in favor of or
 against any possible action. According to published reports this week,
 the FTC's vote ended in a 2-2 tie.


