*********************** ШИНА VESA  НЕ ИМЕЕТ БУДУЩЕГО ******************

 Dell Computer Corp., convinced that Intel Corp.'s PCI local bus is the
 wave of the future, appears to be trying to kill the VESA Local Bus.
 Dell sent out a letter February 12 informing systems manufacturers and
 board makers that their implementations of VESA Local Bus may violate a
 Dell patent, Dell confirmed. If Dell asks manufacturers to stop selling
 the systems, users may be forced to use Intel's technology to speed up
 graphics and other peripherals. Vendors who use the VESA technology
 could lose thousands in development costs and unsellable back stock. At
 the very least, months of litigation and possible licensing fees could
 halt the VESA Local Bus' momentum, giving PCI a chance to gain a
 dominant market share.

 When asked why Dell did not inform VESA of its patent before the
 specification was finalized, William Luther Martin Jr., Dell director of
 licensing and litigation, said, "We've had this patent for over a year.
 At the time [last year] we didn't think VL Bus was going to take off.
 But within the last two months, it has begun to appear that the VL Bus
 would pre-empt the Intel PCI standard, which was a surprise to us."
 However, a Dell representative denied Dell's intention is to kill off
 VESA Local Bus, but said Dell might ask some companies to cease selling
 the systems. Ironically, last year Dell approved the very specification
 it is now contesting. The Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA)
 is an association of vendors that develops graphics-related
 specifications. Dell has been a VESA member for about a year.

 In addition, "VESA has a policy that if you have a patent, you expose
 it," said Tom Ryan, VESA executive director. He refused to comment
 further, saying VESA does not yet have enough information to have chosen
 a course of action. "Given that Dell has had membership in VESA and made
 a tech demo at a VESA meeting at Comdex 91, it's peculiar that they
 would not have advised the VESA members that they had a patent
 application for such technology," said Jon Peddie, publisher of the "PC
 Graphics Report," in Oakland, Calif.
